The morphology of the hydrophilic N-CDs was characterized by TEM image. As shown by TEM images (Fig. 1
                        ), the N-CDs showed the relatively uniform spherical shape, with a mean diameter of 4–12 nm. In addition, HR-TEM image provide the distinct lattice planes with the inter-fringe spacing of 0.24 nm, corresponding to (100) lattice fringes of graphite carbon in N-CDs [34]. As shown in the XRD pattern (Fig. 2
                        ), there is a broad peak located at 25.7o, correspond to the (002) diffraction planes for graphitic carbon materials in N-CDs, which is in accordance with the characteristic inter-layer structural packing [35, 36].

For simplicity and focus, we choose selectively the newly developed hydrophobic N-CDs and tried our best to illustrate the lubrication mechanism. Firstly, we analyzed worn surfaces of steel balls lubricated by pure PAO base oil, PAO with 1.0 wt% of ZDDP and PAO with 1.0 wt% of hydrophobic N-CDs by in combination of 3D images, SEM and EDS analyses (Figs. 9 and 10

                        ). Under the lubrication of pure PAO, the worn surface is not only very rough, but also characterized by a considerably wider and deeper wear scar, indicating that severe scuffing occurred in this case. With the addition of 1.0 wt% ZDDP in PAO, the serious corrosion on the worn surface is detected, which is due to existence of high sulphur and phosphorus elements in ZDDP that transferring from base oils to interface during test. However, the worn surface lubricated by PAO with 1.0 wt% hydrophobic N-CDs is relatively shallow and smooth, while no visible corrosion is detected though some small furrows and scratches appear on the friction surface. The EDS analyses (Table 1
                        ) shows that the content of carbon and nitrogen element on the metal surface is 10.72 wt% and 3.35 wt%, where the carbon content is higher than that of PAO (5.85 wt%) and ZDDP (5.86 wt%) samples, indicating that the carbon core of hydrophobic N-CDs transfer to the surface, thus playing an important role in enhancing properties of friction surface.
